The words 'Regione Puglia' ('Apulia Region') are in gold letters at the top of the flag. The coat of arms of Apulia, a shield atop a crown, is below the lettering. The shield, mounted by the crown of Frederick II, is composed of:

Six bezants at the top represent the six provinces of Apulia;
The octagon represents the Castel del Monte built by Frederick II;
The olive tree is a symbol of peace and brotherhood and a common feature of the Apulian countryside.
The stripes of green and red, set against the white background, are a reference to the national flag of Italy.

The flag consists of the logo of Taipei city imposed on a white background. The logo consists of the name of the city both in English and Chinese with the last letter of the Chinese name ('北') as a partial stroke written in freehand brushwork in different colors. The meaning of the colors are: 

-Red represents enthusiasm and conveys the liveliness and enthusiasm of Taipei people;

-Yellow represents warmth, expressing the friendliness, humanity, and warm tolerance of Taipei people;

-Green represents peace and Taipei's green city that emphasizes environmental protection and happiness; and

-Blue represents rationality and freedom, represents Taipei as an international technological and innovative city, and shows the health and freshness of a waterfront city.

The flag was adopted in 1993 and was modified in 2002 by the legislation of the flag. The flag is divided into 4 red and yellow triangles, the upper and lower colored red and the left and right colored yellow, with the coat of arms of Aragua in the middle. The red symbolizes 'strength, valor, fidelity, joy, and honor to the heroes of the independence struggle'. The yellow symbolizes the tropical climate of the state and its noble and charitable spirit. 

The coat of arms consists of:

-A woman holding a laurel wreath in one of her hands and a palm leaf in the other;

-A saman tree, possibly the Samán de Güere, a still-standing Venezuelan national treasure tree of uncertain age and tall stature;

-A burning house, representing 'the hacienda of the family of national Venezuelan hero Simon Bolívar, which was burnt down during the 1814 Battle of San Mateo'; And

-The inscriptions of the dates allude to the battles that took place in Aragua, one in La Victoria ('Febrero de 1814') and one in San Mateo ('Marzo de 1814').

A popular rhyme explains the colors of the flag:
'Reade wolken;
Blaue lucht;
Gele helmen;
Grien ges;
Wyt sân;
Dat is 't wapen fan Schylgerlân.'

It states that red symbolizes the clouds, blue the sky, yellow the straw, green the grass and white the sand.
